
[1]torment

   TOR'MENT, n. [L. tormentum.; torqueo, torno; Eng. tour; that is, from
   twisting, straining.]

   1. Extreme pain; anguish; the utmost degree of misery, either of body
   or mind.

   The more I see

   Pleasure about me, so much I feel

   Torment within me.

   Lest they also come into this place of torment. Luke 16. Rev.9. 14.

   2. That which gives pain, vexation or misery.

   They brought to him all sick people that were taken with divers
   diseases and torments. Matt. 4.

   3. An engine for casting stones.
